"{\n  \"correct\": \"no\",\n  \"explanation\": \"The np.sinc function returns an array of sinc values, but the sinc function is defined as sinc(x) = sin(pi*x)/(pi*x) if x != 0, and sinc(0) = 1. When x is an integer, the sinc function will return 0 for all non-zero x, but sinc(0) is 1. However, sinc(x) for non-zero integer x is not exactly 0 due to floating point precision issues. Therefore, comparing sinc_result[1] to 0 using '==' may return False due to floating point precision errors.\",\n  \"patch\": \"7,9c7,9\\n< assert sinc_result[0] == 1, \\\"Results not equal to one\\\"\\n< assert sinc_result[1] == 0, \\\"Results not equal to zero\\\"\\n---\\n> np.testing.assert_allclose(sinc_result[0], 1, atol=1e-10)\\n> np.testing.assert_allclose(sinc_result[1:], 0, atol=1e-10)\\n\"\n}"